  91 def is_installable_dir(path):
  92     # type: (STRING_TYPE) -> bool
  93     if pip_shims.shims.is_installable_dir(path):
  94         return True
  95     pyproject_path = os.path.join(path, "pyproject.toml")
  96     if os.path.exists(pyproject_path):
  97         pyproject = Path(pyproject_path)
  98         pyproject_toml = tomlkit.loads(pyproject.read_text())
  99         build_system = pyproject_toml.get("build-system", {}).get("build-backend", "")
 100         if build_system:
 101             return True
 102     return False

 105 def strip_ssh_from_git_uri(uri):
 106     # type: (S) -> S
 107     """Return git+ssh:// formatted URI to git+git@ format"""
 108     if isinstance(uri, six.string_types):
 109         if "git+ssh://" in uri:
 110             parsed = urlparse(uri)
 111             # split the path on the first separating / so we can put the first segment
 112             # into the 'netloc' section with a : separator
 113             path_part, _, path = parsed.path.lstrip("/").partition("/")
 114             path = "/{0}".format(path)
 115             parsed = parsed._replace(
 116                 netloc="{0}:{1}".format(parsed.netloc, path_part), path=path
 117             )
 118             uri = urlunparse(parsed).replace("git+ssh://", "git+", 1)
 119     return uri
 120 
 121 
 122 def add_ssh_scheme_to_git_uri(uri):
 123     # type: (S) -> S
 124     """Cleans VCS uris from pip format"""
 125     if isinstance(uri, six.string_types):
 126         # Add scheme for parsing purposes, this is also what pip does
 127         if uri.startswith("git+") and "://" not in uri:
 128             uri = uri.replace("git+", "git+ssh://", 1)
 129             parsed = urlparse(uri)
 130             if ":" in parsed.netloc:
 131                 netloc, _, path_start = parsed.netloc.rpartition(":")
 132                 path = "/{0}{1}".format(path_start, parsed.path)
 133                 uri = urlunparse(parsed._replace(netloc=netloc, path=path))
 134     return uri

 137 def is_vcs(pipfile_entry):
 138     # type: (PipfileType) -> bool
 139     """Determine if dictionary entry from Pipfile is for a vcs dependency."""
 140     if isinstance(pipfile_entry, Mapping):
 141         return any(key for key in pipfile_entry.keys() if key in VCS_LIST)
 142 
 143     elif isinstance(pipfile_entry, six.string_types):
 144         if not is_valid_url(pipfile_entry) and pipfile_entry.startswith("git+"):
 145             pipfile_entry = add_ssh_scheme_to_git_uri(pipfile_entry)
 146 
 147         parsed_entry = urlsplit(pipfile_entry)
 148         return parsed_entry.scheme in VCS_SCHEMES
 149     return False
 150 
 151 
 152 def is_editable(pipfile_entry):
 153     # type: (PipfileType) -> bool
 154     if isinstance(pipfile_entry, Mapping):
 155         return pipfile_entry.get("editable", False) is True
 156     if isinstance(pipfile_entry, six.string_types):
 157         return pipfile_entry.startswith("-e ")
 158     return False

 161 def is_star(val):
 162     # type: (PipfileType) -> bool
 163     return (isinstance(val, six.string_types) and val == "*") or (
 164         isinstance(val, Mapping) and val.get("version", "") == "*"
 165     )

 168 def convert_entry_to_path(path):
 169     # type: (Dict[S, Union[S, bool, Tuple[S], List[S]]]) -> S
 170     """Convert a pipfile entry to a string"""
 171 
 172     if not isinstance(path, Mapping):
 173         raise TypeError("expecting a mapping, received {0!r}".format(path))
 174 
 175     if not any(key in path for key in ["file", "path"]):
 176         raise ValueError("missing path-like entry in supplied mapping {0!r}".format(path))
 177 
 178     if "file" in path:
 179         path = vistir.path.url_to_path(path["file"])
 180 
 181     elif "path" in path:
 182         path = path["path"]
 183     if not os.name == "nt":
 184         return fs_decode(path)
 185     return Path(fs_decode(path)).as_posix()
 186 
 187 
 188 def is_installable_file(path):
 189     # type: (PipfileType) -> bool
 190     """Determine if a path can potentially be installed"""
 191     from packaging import specifiers
 192 
 193     if isinstance(path, Mapping):
 194         path = convert_entry_to_path(path)
 195 
 196     # If the string starts with a valid specifier operator, test if it is a valid
 197     # specifier set before making a path object (to avoid breaking windows)
 198     if any(path.startswith(spec) for spec in "!=<>~"):
 199         try:
 200             specifiers.SpecifierSet(path)
 201         # If this is not a valid specifier, just move on and try it as a path
 202         except specifiers.InvalidSpecifier:
 203             pass
 204         else:
 205             return False
 206 
 207     parsed = urlparse(path)
 208     is_local = (
 209         not parsed.scheme
 210         or parsed.scheme == "file"
 211         or (len(parsed.scheme) == 1 and os.name == "nt")
 212     )
 213     if parsed.scheme and parsed.scheme == "file":
 214         path = vistir.compat.fs_decode(vistir.path.url_to_path(path))
 215     normalized_path = vistir.path.normalize_path(path)
 216     if is_local and not os.path.exists(normalized_path):
 217         return False
 218 
 219     is_archive = pip_shims.shims.is_archive_file(normalized_path)
 220     is_local_project = os.path.isdir(normalized_path) and is_installable_dir(
 221         normalized_path
 222     )
 223     if is_local and is_local_project or is_archive:
 224         return True
 225 
 226     if not is_local and pip_shims.shims.is_archive_file(parsed.path):
 227         return True
 228 
 229     return False

 232 def get_dist_metadata(dist):
 233     import pkg_resources
 234     from email.parser import FeedParser
 235 
 236     if isinstance(dist, pkg_resources.DistInfoDistribution) and dist.has_metadata(
 237         "METADATA"
 238     ):
 239         metadata = dist.get_metadata("METADATA")
 240     elif dist.has_metadata("PKG-INFO"):
 241         metadata = dist.get_metadata("PKG-INFO")
 242     else:
 243         metadata = ""
 244 
 245     feed_parser = FeedParser()
 246     feed_parser.feed(metadata)
 247     return feed_parser.close()

 250 def get_setup_paths(base_path, subdirectory=None):
 251     # type: (S, Optional[S]) -> Dict[S, Optional[S]]
 252     if base_path is None:
 253         raise TypeError("must provide a path to derive setup paths from")
 254     setup_py = os.path.join(base_path, "setup.py")
 255     setup_cfg = os.path.join(base_path, "setup.cfg")
 256     pyproject_toml = os.path.join(base_path, "pyproject.toml")
 257     if subdirectory is not None:
 258         base_path = os.path.join(base_path, subdirectory)
 259         subdir_setup_py = os.path.join(subdirectory, "setup.py")
 260         subdir_setup_cfg = os.path.join(subdirectory, "setup.cfg")
 261         subdir_pyproject_toml = os.path.join(subdirectory, "pyproject.toml")
 262     if subdirectory and os.path.exists(subdir_setup_py):
 263         setup_py = subdir_setup_py
 264     if subdirectory and os.path.exists(subdir_setup_cfg):
 265         setup_cfg = subdir_setup_cfg
 266     if subdirectory and os.path.exists(subdir_pyproject_toml):
 267         pyproject_toml = subdir_pyproject_toml
 268     return {
 269         "setup_py": setup_py if os.path.exists(setup_py) else None,
 270         "setup_cfg": setup_cfg if os.path.exists(setup_cfg) else None,
 271         "pyproject_toml": pyproject_toml if os.path.exists(pyproject_toml) else None,
 272     }

 275 def prepare_pip_source_args(sources, pip_args=None):
 276     # type: (List[Dict[S, Union[S, bool]]], Optional[List[S]]) -> List[S]
 277     if pip_args is None:
 278         pip_args = []
 279     if sources:
 280         # Add the source to pip9.
 281         pip_args.extend(["-i", sources[0]["url"]])  # type: ignore
 282         # Trust the host if it's not verified.
 283         if not sources[0].get("verify_ssl", True):
 284             pip_args.extend(
 285                 ["--trusted-host", urlparse(sources[0]["url"]).hostname]
 286             )  # type: ignore
 287         # Add additional sources as extra indexes.
 288         if len(sources) > 1:
 289             for source in sources[1:]:
 290                 pip_args.extend(["--extra-index-url", source["url"]])  # type: ignore
 291                 # Trust the host if it's not verified.
 292                 if not source.get("verify_ssl", True):
 293                     pip_args.extend(
 294                         ["--trusted-host", urlparse(source["url"]).hostname]
 295                     )  # type: ignore
 296     return pip_args

 345 class PathAccessError(KeyError, IndexError, TypeError):
 346     """An amalgamation of KeyError, IndexError, and TypeError,
 347     representing what can occur when looking up a path in a nested
 348     object.
 349     """
 350 
 351     def __init__(self, exc, seg, path):
 352         self.exc = exc
 353         self.seg = seg
 354         self.path = path
 355 
 356     def __repr__(self):
 357         cn = self.__class__.__name__
 358         return "%s(%r, %r, %r)" % (cn, self.exc, self.seg, self.path)
 359 
 360     def __str__(self):
 361         return "could not access %r from path %r, got error: %r" % (
 362             self.seg,
 363             self.path,
 364             self.exc,
 365         )
 366 
 367 
 368 def get_path(root, path, default=_UNSET):
 369     """Retrieve a value from a nested object via a tuple representing the
 370     lookup path.
 371     >>> root = {'a': {'b': {'c': [[1], [2], [3]]}}}
 372     >>> get_path(root, ('a', 'b', 'c', 2, 0))
 373     3
 374     The path format is intentionally consistent with that of
 375     :func:`remap`.
 376     One of get_path's chief aims is improved error messaging. EAFP is
 377     great, but the error messages are not.
 378     For instance, ``root['a']['b']['c'][2][1]`` gives back
 379     ``IndexError: list index out of range``
 380     What went out of range where? get_path currently raises
 381     ``PathAccessError: could not access 2 from path ('a', 'b', 'c', 2,
 382     1), got error: IndexError('list index out of range',)``, a
 383     subclass of IndexError and KeyError.
 384     You can also pass a default that covers the entire operation,
 385     should the lookup fail at any level.
 386     Args:
 387        root: The target nesting of dictionaries, lists, or other
 388           objects supporting ``__getitem__``.
 389        path (tuple): A list of strings and integers to be successively
 390           looked up within *root*.
 391        default: The value to be returned should any
 392           ``PathAccessError`` exceptions be raised.
 393     """
 394     if isinstance(path, six.string_types):
 395         path = path.split(".")
 396     cur = root
 397     try:
 398         for seg in path:
 399             try:
 400                 cur = cur[seg]
 401             except (KeyError, IndexError) as exc:
 402                 raise PathAccessError(exc, seg, path)
 403             except TypeError as exc:
 404                 # either string index in a list, or a parent that
 405                 # doesn't support indexing
 406                 try:
 407                     seg = int(seg)
 408                     cur = cur[seg]
 409                 except (ValueError, KeyError, IndexError, TypeError):
 410                     if not getattr(cur, "__iter__", None):
 411                         exc = TypeError("%r object is not indexable" % type(cur).__name__)
 412                     raise PathAccessError(exc, seg, path)
 413     except PathAccessError:
 414         if default is _UNSET:
 415             raise
 416         return default
 417     return cur
 418

 427 # Modified from https://github.com/mahmoud/boltons/blob/master/boltons/iterutils.py
 428 def dict_path_enter(path, key, value):
 429     if isinstance(value, six.string_types):
 430         return value, False
 431     elif isinstance(value, (Mapping, dict)):
 432         return value.__class__(), ItemsView(value)
 433     elif isinstance(value, tomlkit.items.Array):
 434         return value.__class__([], value.trivia), enumerate(value)
 435     elif isinstance(value, (Sequence, list)):
 436         return value.__class__(), enumerate(value)
 437     elif isinstance(value, (Set, set)):
 438         return value.__class__(), enumerate(value)
 439     else:
 440         return value, False
 441 
 442 
 443 def dict_path_exit(path, key, old_parent, new_parent, new_items):
 444     ret = new_parent
 445     if isinstance(new_parent, (Mapping, dict)):
 446         vals = dict(new_items)
 447         try:
 448             new_parent.update(new_items)
 449         except AttributeError:
 450             # Handle toml containers specifically
 451             try:
 452                 new_parent.update(vals)
 453             # Now use default fallback if needed
 454             except AttributeError:
 455                 ret = new_parent.__class__(vals)
 456     elif isinstance(new_parent, tomlkit.items.Array):
 457         vals = tomlkit.items.item([v for i, v in new_items])
 458         try:
 459             new_parent._value.extend(vals._value)
 460         except AttributeError:
 461             ret = tomlkit.items.item(vals)
 462     elif isinstance(new_parent, (Sequence, list)):
 463         vals = [v for i, v in new_items]
 464         try:
 465             new_parent.extend(vals)
 466         except AttributeError:
 467             ret = new_parent.__class__(vals)  # tuples
 468     elif isinstance(new_parent, (Set, set)):
 469         vals = [v for i, v in new_items]
 470         try:
 471             new_parent.update(vals)
 472         except AttributeError:
 473             ret = new_parent.__class__(vals)  # frozensets
 474     else:
 475         raise RuntimeError("unexpected iterable type: %r" % type(new_parent))
 476     return ret

 479 def remap(
 480     root, visit=default_visit, enter=dict_path_enter, exit=dict_path_exit, **kwargs
 481 ):
 482     """The remap ("recursive map") function is used to traverse and
 483     transform nested structures. Lists, tuples, sets, and dictionaries
 484     are just a few of the data structures nested into heterogenous
 485     tree-like structures that are so common in programming.
 486     Unfortunately, Python's built-in ways to manipulate collections
 487     are almost all flat. List comprehensions may be fast and succinct,
 488     but they do not recurse, making it tedious to apply quick changes
 489     or complex transforms to real-world data.
 490     remap goes where list comprehensions cannot.
 491     Here's an example of removing all Nones from some data:
 492     >>> from pprint import pprint
 493     >>> reviews = {'Star Trek': {'TNG': 10, 'DS9': 8.5, 'ENT': None},
 494     ...            'Babylon 5': 6, 'Dr. Who': None}
 495     >>> pprint(remap(reviews, lambda p, k, v: v is not None))
 496     {'Babylon 5': 6, 'Star Trek': {'DS9': 8.5, 'TNG': 10}}
 497     Notice how both Nones have been removed despite the nesting in the
 498     dictionary. Not bad for a one-liner, and that's just the beginning.
 499     See `this remap cookbook`_ for more delicious recipes.
 500     .. _this remap cookbook: http://sedimental.org/remap.html
 501     remap takes four main arguments: the object to traverse and three
 502     optional callables which determine how the remapped object will be
 503     created.
 504     Args:
 505         root: The target object to traverse. By default, remap
 506             supports iterables like :class:`list`, :class:`tuple`,
 507             :class:`dict`, and :class:`set`, but any object traversable by
 508             *enter* will work.
 509         visit (callable): This function is called on every item in
 510             *root*. It must accept three positional arguments, *path*,
 511             *key*, and *value*. *path* is simply a tuple of parents'
 512             keys. *visit* should return the new key-value pair. It may
 513             also return ``True`` as shorthand to keep the old item
 514             unmodified, or ``False`` to drop the item from the new
 515             structure. *visit* is called after *enter*, on the new parent.
 516             The *visit* function is called for every item in root,
 517             including duplicate items. For traversable values, it is
 518             called on the new parent object, after all its children
 519             have been visited. The default visit behavior simply
 520             returns the key-value pair unmodified.
 521         enter (callable): This function controls which items in *root*
 522             are traversed. It accepts the same arguments as *visit*: the
 523             path, the key, and the value of the current item. It returns a
 524             pair of the blank new parent, and an iterator over the items
 525             which should be visited. If ``False`` is returned instead of
 526             an iterator, the value will not be traversed.
 527             The *enter* function is only called once per unique value. The
 528             default enter behavior support mappings, sequences, and
 529             sets. Strings and all other iterables will not be traversed.
 530         exit (callable): This function determines how to handle items
 531             once they have been visited. It gets the same three
 532             arguments as the other functions -- *path*, *key*, *value*
 533             -- plus two more: the blank new parent object returned
 534             from *enter*, and a list of the new items, as remapped by
 535             *visit*.
 536             Like *enter*, the *exit* function is only called once per
 537             unique value. The default exit behavior is to simply add
 538             all new items to the new parent, e.g., using
 539             :meth:`list.extend` and :meth:`dict.update` to add to the
 540             new parent. Immutable objects, such as a :class:`tuple` or
 541             :class:`namedtuple`, must be recreated from scratch, but
 542             use the same type as the new parent passed back from the
 543             *enter* function.
 544         reraise_visit (bool): A pragmatic convenience for the *visit*
 545             callable. When set to ``False``, remap ignores any errors
 546             raised by the *visit* callback. Items causing exceptions
 547             are kept. See examples for more details.
 548     remap is designed to cover the majority of cases with just the
 549     *visit* callable. While passing in multiple callables is very
 550     empowering, remap is designed so very few cases should require
 551     passing more than one function.
 552     When passing *enter* and *exit*, it's common and easiest to build
 553     on the default behavior. Simply add ``from boltons.iterutils import
 554     default_enter`` (or ``default_exit``), and have your enter/exit
 555     function call the default behavior before or after your custom
 556     logic. See `this example`_.
 557     Duplicate and self-referential objects (aka reference loops) are
 558     automatically handled internally, `as shown here`_.
 559     .. _this example: http://sedimental.org/remap.html#sort_all_lists
 560     .. _as shown here: http://sedimental.org/remap.html#corner_cases
 561     """
 562     # TODO: improve argument formatting in sphinx doc
 563     # TODO: enter() return (False, items) to continue traverse but cancel copy?
 564     if not callable(visit):
 565         raise TypeError("visit expected callable, not: %r" % visit)
 566     if not callable(enter):
 567         raise TypeError("enter expected callable, not: %r" % enter)
 568     if not callable(exit):
 569         raise TypeError("exit expected callable, not: %r" % exit)
 570     reraise_visit = kwargs.pop("reraise_visit", True)
 571     if kwargs:
 572         raise TypeError("unexpected keyword arguments: %r" % kwargs.keys())
 573 
 574     path, registry, stack = (), {}, [(None, root)]
 575     new_items_stack = []
 576     while stack:
 577         key, value = stack.pop()
 578         id_value = id(value)
 579         if key is _REMAP_EXIT:
 580             key, new_parent, old_parent = value
 581             id_value = id(old_parent)
 582             path, new_items = new_items_stack.pop()
 583             value = exit(path, key, old_parent, new_parent, new_items)
 584             registry[id_value] = value
 585             if not new_items_stack:
 586                 continue
 587         elif id_value in registry:
 588             value = registry[id_value]
 589         else:
 590             res = enter(path, key, value)
 591             try:
 592                 new_parent, new_items = res
 593             except TypeError:
 594                 # TODO: handle False?
 595                 raise TypeError(
 596                     "enter should return a tuple of (new_parent,"
 597                     " items_iterator), not: %r" % res
 598                 )
 599             if new_items is not False:
 600                 # traverse unless False is explicitly passed
 601                 registry[id_value] = new_parent
 602                 new_items_stack.append((path, []))
 603                 if value is not root:
 604                     path += (key,)
 605                 stack.append((_REMAP_EXIT, (key, new_parent, value)))
 606                 if new_items:
 607                     stack.extend(reversed(list(new_items)))
 608                 continue
 609         if visit is _orig_default_visit:
 610             # avoid function call overhead by inlining identity operation
 611             visited_item = (key, value)
 612         else:
 613             try:
 614                 visited_item = visit(path, key, value)
 615             except Exception:
 616                 if reraise_visit:
 617                     raise
 618                 visited_item = True
 619             if visited_item is False:
 620                 continue  # drop
 621             elif visited_item is True:
 622                 visited_item = (key, value)
 623             # TODO: typecheck?
 624             #    raise TypeError('expected (key, value) from visit(),'
 625             #                    ' not: %r' % visited_item)
 626         try:
 627             new_items_stack[-1][1].append(visited_item)
 628         except IndexError:
 629             raise TypeError("expected remappable root, not: %r" % root)
 630     return value
 631 
 632 
 633 def merge_items(target_list, sourced=False):
 634     if not sourced:
 635         target_list = [(id(t), t) for t in target_list]
 636 
 637     ret = None
 638     source_map = {}
 639 
 640     def remerge_enter(path, key, value):
 641         new_parent, new_items = dict_path_enter(path, key, value)
 642         if ret and not path and key is None:
 643             new_parent = ret
 644 
 645         try:
 646             cur_val = get_path(ret, path + (key,))
 647         except KeyError as ke:
 648             pass
 649         else:
 650             new_parent = cur_val
 651 
 652         return new_parent, new_items
 653 
 654     def remerge_exit(path, key, old_parent, new_parent, new_items):
 655         return dict_path_exit(path, key, old_parent, new_parent, new_items)
 656 
 657     for t_name, target in target_list:
 658         if sourced:
 659 
 660             def remerge_visit(path, key, value):
 661                 source_map[path + (key,)] = t_name
 662                 return True
 663 
 664         else:
 665             remerge_visit = default_visit
 666 
 667         ret = remap(target, enter=remerge_enter, visit=remerge_visit, exit=remerge_exit)
 668 
 669     if not sourced:
 670         return ret
 671     return ret, source_map
